{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Request payload sent to the external API includes the full taxonomy label list every time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: taxonomy/config -> request builder -> API client. A pure Unit test of a helper can miss dropped fields at wiring time (MOCK-MISS). No real OS/network behavior is required to reproduce; a fake client that captures outbound payload is sufficient, so not System (REAL-INFRA/INTEGRATION-BRAKE-a). Correctness does not depend on model judgment/content, so not Agentic (INTEGRATION-BRAKE-b).","test_description":"Wire classifier module with a spy/fake API client. Invoke classify with a known taxonomy and assert captured outbound request contains exactly the complete taxonomy labels (no omissions/reordering loss if order is contractually relevant).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test explicitly needs module-to-client wiring, matching Integration.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"If API returns a label outside taxonomy, module returns \"unknown\".","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior is response handoff + normalization policy at boundary of API adapter and classifier service, not just isolated string mapping (MOCK-MISS). A stubbed API response can reproduce the real failure; no real network/OS required, so System is disqualified by behavior text \"When the API returns a label\" (can be simulated) (REJECTION-GATE). No dependence on real model quality; the out-of-taxonomy value is explicit, so not Agentic.","test_description":"Use classifier wired to a fake API client returning e.g. \"sports\" for taxonomy {legal, technical, financial, other}. Assert final returned label is \"unknown\" and raw unexpected label is not forwarded.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Covers boundary interaction; Unit-only would risk missing wiring defects.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Normalization is deterministic for identical raw API responses.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior text names a single local transformation: \"normalization step always produces the same final label.\" No cross-module requirement, no I/O, no external dependency; failure is local function/object logic.","test_description":"Call normalization function/object repeatedly with identical raw response fixtures (case variants/whitespace/punctuation as needed). Assert identical final label each run and no hidden state influence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test is purely local and does not require higher infrastructure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Across repeated live API calls for same input, label stays consistent unless provider response changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on real model output consistency under repeated live calls (LLM-DEP). A mock/stub would always pass and hide real nondeterminism (MOCK-HIDE). Not Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification, not multi-agentic staged pipeline (MULTI-STEP).","test_description":"Run N repeated real classification calls for the same document+taxonomy, recording provider raw response and final label. Assert final label changes only when raw provider output changes; flag unexplained drift. Use tolerance/reporting for stochastic variance policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Requires real model behavior; lower levels cannot detect nondeterministic drift.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces configured token budget before dispatch (truncate/reject per policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure mode is ordering/handoff: budget enforcement must occur before dispatch, and dispatched payload must reflect policy outcome. Unit tests on tokenizer/policy logic alone can miss sending untrimmed payload due to wiring/order bugs (MOCK-MISS). No real OS/network required; fake client can assert dispatch/no-dispatch and payload shape, so not System. No model-output dependence, so not Agentic.","test_description":"Wire classifier with fake API client and deterministic token counter fixture. Test over-budget document under each policy: reject => no client call and policy error/marker; truncate => one client call with token count <= budget. Verify enforcement happened pre-dispatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Behavior explicitly spans constructor/enforcer/dispatcher interaction.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for typical document remains within configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on provider-reported usage, which requires real external API interaction and real HTTP response fields (REAL-INFRA). In-process fakes can hide tokenizer/accounting mismatches with provider (MOCK-HIDE). Agentic was considered but rejected because assertion is about usage accounting, not model decision quality; behavior text is \"Provider-reported token usage\" (REJECTION-GATE).","test_description":"Execute real API call(s) with representative document and configured budget in a controlled environment. Read provider usage metadata from real response and assert reported tokens <= budget. Capture request/response IDs for reproducibility.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Needs real provider accounting; lower levels cannot validate this boundary.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"On provider rate-limit signal, module waits and retries instead of returning immediate error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure boundary is retry orchestration across classifier and API client on a specific error signal (429/rate-limit). This is reproducible with deterministic fake client responses and controllable clock; real network is not required, so System is disqualified by behavior text focused on logic \"waits and retries\" (REJECTION-GATE). No dependence on model output quality, so not Agentic.","test_description":"Use fake API client scripted to return rate-limit signal then success, plus fake clock/sleeper. Assert module performs wait/backoff, retries expected count, and eventually returns success to caller rather than immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration is required to verify orchestrated retry path across modules.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
